      "id": 100,
      "title": "Mole",
      "description": "Deep, rich chilli sauce for tacos or to server with smoked pork.",
      "contents": "# Ingredients\r\n\r\n*   Dried ancho chilies (About 75g)\n\r\n*   1 large onion\n\r\n*   2 green chillies\n\r\n*   3 cloves of garlic (unpeeled)\n\r\n*   1 handful of raw peanuts\n\r\n*   1 tbsp chipotle in adobe\n\r\n*   1 tbsp Honey\n\r\n*   2 tsp coriander seeds\n\r\n*   2 tsp cumin seeds\n\r\n*   1 tsp cinnamon\n\r\n*   1 tsp salt\n\r\n*   Olive oil\n\r\n*   2 tbsp tomato puree\n\n\r\n\r\n# Directions\r\n\r\n*   Roughly chop, destem and deseed the dried and green chilies.\n\r\n*   Roughly chop the onion into quarters. Put dried and green chillies, onions and garlic in a hot, dry frypan and turn occasionally until everything is lightly charred.\n\r\n*   In a medium saucepan fry the tomato puree in olive oil\n\r\n*   Add all charred ingredients from the frypan (peeling the garlic cloves).\n\r\n*   Top up with enough water to just cover everything and bring to a simmer.\n\r\n*   Fry the coriander and cumin seeds in the dry frypan and grind. Add, along with the honey, salt, cinnamon and chipotle to the saucepan.\n\r\n*   Gently simmer until the dried chillies are completely soft.\n\r\n*   Take off the heat and allow to cool a little.\n\r\n*   Meanwhile, toast the peanuts in the dry frypan and then place in a food processor along with the contents of the saucepan.\n\r\n*   Blitz to a thick paste (as smooth or as chunky as you like). Add some water if it is too thick. Check for salt.\n\r\n*   When ready to use, return to the saucepan and reheat, or it can be eaten cold. It is better the next day.\n\n",
